            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-35367",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The nohup utility in uutils coreutils creates its default output file, ..."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The nohup utility in uutils coreutils creates its default output file, nohup.out, without specifying explicit restricted permissions. This causes the file to inherit umask-based permissions, typically resulting in a world-readable file (0644). In multi-user environments, this allows any user on the system to read the captured stdout/stderr output of a command, potentially exposing sensitive information. This behavior diverges from GNU coreutils, which creates nohup.out with owner-only (0600) permissions."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-35367",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-35367\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nPackage: rust-coreutils\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2026-35367](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-35367)\nThe nohup utility in uutils coreutils creates its default output file, nohup.out, without specifying explicit restricted permissions. This causes the file to inherit umask-based permissions, typically resulting in a world-readable file (0644). In multi-user environments, this allows any user on the system to read the captured stdout/stderr output of a command, potentially exposing sensitive information. This behavior diverges from GNU coreutils, which creates nohup.out with owner-only (0600) permissions.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-35367**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|MEDIUM|rust-coreutils||[CVE-2026-35367](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-35367)|\n\nThe nohup utility in uutils coreutils creates its default output file, nohup.out, without specifying explicit restricted permissions. This causes the file to inherit umask-based permissions, typically resulting in a world-readable file (0644). In multi-user environments, this allows any user on the system to read the captured stdout/stderr output of a command, potentially exposing sensitive information. This behavior diverges from GNU coreutils, which creates nohup.out with owner-only (0600) permissions."
              },
              "properties": {
                "precision": "very-high",
